<Project>
  <Target Name="SerdeSourceGenClean" AfterTargets="Clean">
    <!-- Remove this project's own Serde-generated artefacts on Clean:
         obj/serde-generated/ — codecs / dispatch / entry-point.
         Do NOT remove fable-generated/ here: this targets file is imported by
         every project that references Serde.FS (including Shared/Domain
         projects), but the fable-generated/ folder is OWNED by the backend
         project's generator (Serde.FS.Json). If we cleaned it here, a
         WebFable Rebuild that transitively cleans Shared would wipe the file
         before WebFable's compile sees it, breaking the Fable client. The
         owner-driven cleanup lives in Serde.FS.Json.targets's
         SerdeJsonCleanFableClients target. -->
    <RemoveDir Directories="$(IntermediateOutputPath)serde-generated" />
  </Target>

  <!-- Auto-include generated Fable client files written by a sibling project's
       generator when the interface is annotated with [<GenerateFableClient>].
       This MUST be an evaluation-time ItemGroup (not a target):
         • Fable 5's project cracker invokes `FscCommandLineArgs` (not
           `CoreCompile`), so any `BeforeTargets="CoreCompile"` target would
           never fire under Fable and the generated file would be invisible
           to the Fable build.
         • The IDE's F# language service runs design-time builds that also
           skip `CoreCompile`, so the same problem appears there as red
           squiggles even when `dotnet build` succeeds.
       An evaluation-time ItemGroup is target-invariant: the items are part
       of the project's static item list, picked up by ANY MSBuild consumer
       (dotnet build, Fable cracker, IDE design-time build) regardless of
       which targets they invoke.

       Cold-start note: this requires the file to exist at MSBuild evaluation
       time. The file is written by a sibling backend project's generator
       during its own build, so for a green-field workspace the user must
       build the backend (e.g. the ASP.NET server) once before Fable can see
       the client — subsequent builds work transparently. The Items appear
       at the END of the Compile list (this .targets file is imported after
       the consuming .fsproj is evaluated), which is the right order because
       the generated client references types defined elsewhere in Domain. -->
  <ItemGroup Condition="Exists('$(MSBuildProjectDirectory)\fable-generated')">
    <!-- Visible="false" hides these from Solution Explorer (and other IDE
         explorers that honor MSBuild item metadata) so the auto-generated
         Fable client doesn't clutter the consumer's project node — the user
         never wrote these files and shouldn't have to look at them. They
         remain active Compile items so the F# compiler / Fable's cracker
         still pick them up. -->
    <Compile Include="$(MSBuildProjectDirectory)\fable-generated\*.fs"
             Visible="false" />
  </ItemGroup>
</Project>
